<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan-War     10-08 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan-War,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil War Ravages Civilian Life in Southern Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MALAKAL, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matchstick-thin, naked children with
swollen bellies stand under a harsh sun, chewing dried, uncooked
fish. Their emaciated elders sit with blank stares, gazing toward
the horizon.
   Half the 50,000 people living in this wretched Nile riverport
are seeking shelter in Malakal from the horrors of a seemingly
interminable civil war, refugees in their own country.
   Sanitary services are non-existent, and malaria and typhoid run
rampant. Those who are sick have but one dilapidated hospital to
turn to, with only a handful of doctors and almost no medical
supplies.
   Malakal, capital of the southern Upper Nile region, is a
microcosm of Sudan's southland, an area the size of Texas laid
waste by 6{ years of warfare and famine.
   A massive international relief operation prevented a repeat of
the mass starvation experienced in the summer of 1988. But the
rebellion's accumulated effects continue to wreak havoc on the
region's desperate civilians.
   Government troops control Malakal, 425 miles south of the
capital, Khartoum, as they do most southern population centers.
Nevertheless, rebels of the Sudan People's Liberation Army stake
out areas on its perimeter as freely as they move about in more
than 90 percent of the southern countryside.
   Militarily, the war has basically been at a standstill for
months. Both sides agreed in April to quiet their guns to let
relief goods go through.
   A military junta took power in Khartoum June 30, promising to
end the war, and has extended the truce each month. The rebels have
gone along.
   But political maneuvering over how and when to talk peace
continues, leaving the people of Malakal and the rest of the south
struggling, but surviving.
   ``People may think we're all dead,'' said Joseph Maker, a
government employee, ``but we're still living, despite the war.''
   A chieftain of the Shuluk tribe told a visiting reporter: ``Life
is going on here. We are life. We are giving birth, and we are
eating. Although very little.''
   The United Nations says 250,000 southerners died a year ago of
starvation or disease in a famine caused by the war. Other Western
relief workers estimate the death toll at twice that.
   To prevent a recurrence, the U.N. agencies organized Operation
Lifeline Sudan to position 105,000 tons of relief goods in key
transit points for distribution to displaced people after
monsoon-like summer rains isolated them this year. Organizers say
80 percent of the goods was positioned in time.
   James O'Neil, regional monitor of the U.N. World Food Program,
said government and rebels are negotiating the dispatch of a third
convoy of Nile River barges with additional relief for the Upper
Nile.
   The program has had to overcome logistical and political
problems, he said. There were too few workers for unloading the
barges en route and inadequate storage facilities. Local officials
complained about unfair distribution. As displaced people flooded
the towns, the numbers of people who had to be cared for kept
changing.
   Malakal still faces life-threatening problems, especially in
health care.
   ``Malaria and typhoid are everywhere, and we have no chloroquine
(malaria medicine) or syringes,'' said Lt. Col. Galwak Deng,
military governor for the Upper Nile.
   ``We have only one general practitioner, when we need at least
24. We have some 500 (doses) of medication, which would be consumed
in one day if we were to use them, but we have more than 600
patients coming in every day.''
   Doctors and nurses said the town's lone hospital has 14 badly
equipped wards with about 500 beds. Hospital records show at least
two deaths a day from malaria or typhoid.
   Hospital staff are helped by three doctors of the French
organization Medicins Sans Frontieres and some military doctors.
   ``These deaths are only the ones in the hospital,'' said one of
the French physicians, who identified himself as Dr. Pathot. ``We
have no car at all, nor an ambulance, so if somebody is going to
die, he may do it before coming to us.
   ``We can't say how many die every day.''
   As the civilian populace struggles to survive, the army has been
trying to reopen the town's 10 schools, closed for almost three
years.
   Two primary schools have been reopened. A reporter touring them
found the classes had no desks, stools or blackboards.
   Children sat on the ground, their teachers instructing them to
read and write by using the earth as a blackboard and a stick as
chalk.
</TEXT>
