<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 0121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Pope-Asia 1stLd-Writethru a0515 10-08 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Asia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0515,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Appeals For End to Ideological Rifts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Sunday mass; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II appealed Sunday for
an end to ideological divisions worldwide and said the bitter
struggle that divides north and south Korea symbolized suffering.
   ``East is divided from west, north from south,'' John Paul said
at an open air mass attended by 700,000. He appealed for the world
to give up mistrust, hostility and conflict ``to live in peace and
brotherhood.''
   ``The Korean nation is symbolic of a world divided and not yet
able to become one in peace and justice,'' the pope said, speaking
alternately in Korean and English.
   The vast crowd, many of whom had lined up before dawn, waved
white Korean flags and some wept as the pope entered an immense
plaza for the mass.
   Hundreds of singers burst into hymn as the pope walked along a
red carpet toward a four-story stage and altar, tiered with
thousands of red, white, yellow and pink flowers and flanked by
colorful banners.
   Plain-clothed South Korean security agents carrying submachine
guns ringed the stage, and 11,000 police were deployed on the
outskirts of the plaza. Those who attended the mass had to pass
through metal detectors.
   About 2,000 priests, aided by 2,000 women in traditional Korean
gowns, served communion, while 1,200 white doves were released as a
sign of peace.
   At an earlier meeting with President Roh Tae-woo, the pope asked
the South Korean leader to make every effort to achieve full
democracy and eradicate the nation's legacy of authoritarian rule,
a Vatican spokesman said.
   John Paul told Roh that South Koreans want full democratic
rights and freedoms, the spokesman said.
   John Paul II began his Asian pilgrimage in Seoul Saturday. About
1,000 dissidents and radical students staged an anti-government
rally at Sogang University to urge the pope to speak out on human
rights abuses in South Korea.
   An equal number of riot police surrounded the campus, but made
no move to halt Saturday's protest. The students dispersed
peacefully after demanding the release of jailed dissidents,
including South Korean clergymen charged with visiting North Korea
for unification talks.
   John Paul arrived in Seoul after for the first time flying
across the Soviet Union and sending greetings to Soviet President
Mikhail Gorbachev in a sign of remarkably improved Vatican-Soviet
relations. He expressed hope he would soon visit Moscow.
   He immediately took up the issue of Korean reunification, which
has divided the influential Catholic community in South Korea.
   Addressing himself to the ``dear people of Korea,'' John Paul
said: ``In the face of the tragic division which continues to
separate your own people, do you not have the urgent mission to
prove to a world torn by mistrust, strife and hatred that mankind
does have the resources to end division and war, and to forge an
enduring peace?''
   The Korean Peninsula, divided in 1945, is the site of one of the
world's most bitter ideological confrontations. The capitalist
South and the totalitarian North, which fought to a bloody
stalemate in the Korean War, clash frequently and maintain huge
armies along their 150-mile border.
   They still are technically at war since no peace treaty was
signed at the end of the Korean War in 1953.
   A heated debate broke out in the Catholic community after a
dissident priest visited North Korea in July to escort home a
radical college student. The two claimed the trip was to promote
reunification, but the Seoul government called it an illegal
contact with an enemy state.
   The priest and student were arrested when they crossed back
across the border. Three other priests were jailed for organizing
the priest's trip without government approval.
   After South Korea, the pope travels on to Indonesia and East
Timor, and then to the Indian Ocean island nation of Mauritius. He
is to return to Rome Oct. 16.
   The trip is the Polish-born pope's 44th foreign pilgrimage.
</TEXT>
