<FIRST>u i BC-SriLanka     10-08 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sri Lanka,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaffna Newspaper Staff Abducted, Allegedly by Tamils</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil guerrillas abducted 18
journalists from their newspaper office and said they would be put
to work on a new Tamil publication, a reporter who fled during the
raid said Sunday.
   The armed militants burst into the Jaffna offices of Eelanadu,
Sri Lanka's oldest Tamil language newspaper, on Thursday, the
journalist said in Colombo.
   He said he was one of five reporters who bolted to freedom
before the abductors drove away with the reporters. The journalist
asked not to be identified out of fear for his safety.
   ``I want to go back to Jaffna and my newspaper,'' he said.
   The Colombo office of Eelanadu, which means Sri Lanka in Tamil,
confirmed the attack but gave no details.
   The journalist said the gunmen belonged to the Eelam Peoples
Revolutionary Liberation Front, which is supported by India and
opposes the largest Tamil militia, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam.
   According to the journalist, the abductors said they were going
to publish a new newspaper called Viduthalai, which means
liberation in the Tamil language. He has provided reliable
information in the past.
   The Tigers are fighting Indian peacekeeping troops sent to Sri
Lanka to disarm them in 1987. The Liberation Front and other Tamil
militants accepted the Indian-brokered peace plan.
   The Front and the Tigers once jointly sought independence for
the Tamil minority in Sri Lanka, where the government and military
are dominated by the Sinhalese majority.
   The ethnic violence in Tamil-dominated northeastern Sri Lanka
has claimed more than 11,000 lives in the past six years.
   The Liberation Front closed Eelanadu and two other Tamil
newspapers in Jaffna, 180 miles northeast of Colombo, on Sept. 20
after the publications carried paid advertisements commemorating
the second anniversary of the death of a Tiger rebel leader.
   In February, the Tigers blew up Eelanadu's offices after the
newspaper carried stories that the Tigers considered pro-Indian.
Eelanadu, which was founded 30 years ago and has a circulation of
10,000, resumed publication in May with a skeleton staff.
</TEXT>
