<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 28 in Leaked Security Documents Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said they arrested 28
people Sunday in connection with the recent leaks of security files
identifying alleged Irish Republican Army suspects.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary would not comment on British news
reports that the detainees were members of the Ulster Defense
Regiment, the locally recruited and mostly part-time force of the
British army.
   A police spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British
custom, said 300 uniformed and plainclothes officers were involved
in raids on 30 houses during which security documents and
ammunition were also seized.
   Charges had not been filed.
   The raids follow an investigation by Deputy Chief Constable John
Stevens of the Cambridgeshire, England, police force into
allegations that a group of police and Ulster Defense Regiment
members leaked secret files on IRA suspects to the media.
   Protestant gunmen have claimed they used such documents to pick
targets, including a Roman Catholic man slain in August.
   Stevens said in a statement that ``a number of men'' were
arrested and houses searched in the greater Belfast area as part of
the inquiry.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
unite the predominantly Protestant province with the Roman Catholic
Republic of Ireland. The 20-year struggle has claimed more than
2,700 lives.
