<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 1150EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     10-08 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Urge U.S. Role in Middle East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian leaders urged the United States on
Sunday to pressure Israel to begin peace talks and said Israel's
rejection of a proposed meeting with Palestinians in Egypt will
lead to more violence in the uprising.
   A leading Labor Party politician, Moshe Shahal, said U.S. help
in choosing Palestinian delegates to talk with Israel could
``rescue the political situation'' following Friday's rejection of
the Egypt-sponsored dialogue.
   In the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, businesses were closed
by a general strike, the first of a three-day shutdown ordered by
the uprising's PLO-backed underground leaders to step up the revolt
against Israeli rule of the lands.
   The Israeli army closed off the territories Sunday afternoon,
blocking Palestinians from entering Israel on Yom Kippur, the
Jewish day of atonement, which began at sundown.
   Radwan Abu Ayyash, one of the Palestinian leaders reportedly
suggested by Egyptian leader Hosni Mubarak to meet with Israeli
representatives, said only U.S. pressure would lead to the dialogue
suggested by the Egyptian president.
   ``The United States must take a more active and serious role to
convince the Israelis to hold the meeting proposed by Mubarak,'' he
said in a telephone interview.
   Abu Ayyash _ head of the West Bank's Arab Journalists
Association and a supporter of Yasser Arafat's mainstream Palestine
Liberation Organization faction, Fatah _ urged the U.S. government
to step up its dialogue with the PLO ``to counter the Israeli
decision.''
   Mubarak's offer was rejected because Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc objected to the Egyptian leader's
call to include Palestinians deported from the occupied territories
in peace talks. Shamir said including the exiles would amount to
allowing the PLO into the peace process.
   The center-left Labor Party, Likud's partner in the coalition
government, urged Israel to accept Mubarak's offer. But the
policy-making inner Cabinet vote produced a 6-6 tie along political
lines, which amounted to a rejection of the Egyptian offer.
   Assad Saftawi, a Gaza Strip school principal and another
reported choice of Mubarak for the talks, said he was shocked that
Mubarak's offer was rejected.
   ``The decision will bring waves of violence and extremism,''
Saftawi said. ``The blame is on Israel.''
   Saftawi and Abu Ayyash predicted more violence in the
Palestinian uprising if there were no progress toward peace. The
revolt, which begins its 23rd month Monday, already has led to the
deaths of 585 Palestinians and 40 Israelis.
   ``Palestinian moderation has its limits. If there is no
achievement, then our people will go back to extremism,'' Saftawi
told the AP.
   Members of Likud maintained, meanwhile, that the inner Cabinet
vote did not halt progress toward peace.
   ``The peace process ... does not depend on one vote in the
Cabinet,'' said Ehud Olmert, the minister in charge of Arab affairs.
   He told Israel radio that the government could still agree to
meet a Palestinian delegation if the members were acceptable to
Israel.
   His Likud colleague, Foreign Minister Moshe Arens, blamed last
week's rejection on the ``stubbornness'' of Labor in forcing a vote
on Mubarak's proposal. He said the vote should have been put off
until after Israel received an expected U.S. proposal to assist in
forming a Palestinian delegation to the peace talks.
   But Shahal, energy minister in the coalition Cabinet, said Arens
never requested a delay and came to Friday's meeting with only a
vague notion of what the United States might propose.
   ``If there is an American proposal, which we haven't heard
explicitly from the foreign minister ... this could rescue the
political situation,'' he said.
   Shamir, speaking on the radio in a Yom Kippur address, called
Israelis ``seekers of peace'' but said Israel has survived only
through armed might.
   ``The army ... has proved to our enemies and the whole world
that it is impossible to defeat us,'' he said.
</TEXT>
