<DOCNO> AP891008-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 1217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-Dean     10-08 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Dean,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Dean Files Confirm Her Power, Politics At HUD</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: St German, no period, is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When then-House Banking Committee Chairman
Fernand J. St Germain asked for help from the Department of Housing
and Urban Development in June 1985, an agency official asked
Deborah Gore Dean whether he should get it.
   ``Absolutely!!!'' was her short, but emphatic, answer.
   And when Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan wrote HUD about a problem
in his state not long before an important vote, Dean swung into
action.
   ``This looks like trouble,'' she wrote an aide. ``We need Levin
too much. ... Please call him, tell him that we'll do whatever we
can.''
   But when Jesse Jackson wanted her boss, HUD Secretary Samuel
Pierce, to accompany him to a housing project devastated by a
hurricane, Dean frowned at the request.
   ``Respectfully decline,'' she wrote.
   Those episodes, detailed in more than 20,000 pages of Dean's
files, are but three of hundreds of glimpses of the politics of HUD
during the Reagan administration, and of the power Dean held as
Pierce's close aide.
   Dean, who had no experience in housing and only a brief stint in
government before coming to work at HUD, is a central figure in the
congressional investigation of favoritism and mismanagement at HUD.
Like Pierce, she has refused to testify by citing her right against
self-incrimination.
   Her files show she was also a central figure in agency affairs,
keeping Pierce apprised of important developments, endorsing
projects she liked and cracking down on work that didn't satisfy
her.
   ``You all must bear down _ no more garbage for (Pierce's)
signature,'' she said in a July 1985 note to three HUD officials
who worked on a letter for Pierce. ``He deserves better work from
his assistants. Review my notes and do four Hail Mary's.''
   When a request from someone who could help HUD _ like St
Germain, whose committee controlled the agency's budget _ reached
Dean's desk, she made sure it was handled quickly, often sending
critical notes to aides who had not responded to the requests
sooner.
   She was just as keenly aware of the other side of the political
fence, rejecting Pierce appearances with Jackson and another
prominent black, South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu, both of
whom had major differences with the Reagan administration.
   Her files, released last week under the Freedom of Information
Act, show she was swamped with requests for help from developers,
consultants, local housing officials, city councilors and mayors,
and members of Congress.
   For some, she arranged meetings or telephone conversations with
Pierce. For others, she made sure their proposals were routed to
the proper agency official, sometimes adding her endorsement.
   ``Please give these people all the help you can,'' she wrote to
a deputy when sending him a proposal for a HUD grant, which was
later approved.
   On occasion, she even delved into the realm of social director _
securing White House tour passes for then-Columbus, Ohio, City
Councilor David E. Cain in 1983 and an invitation to a dinner in
honor of former President Nixon for one of Pierce's former law
partners in 1985.
   ``My family and I enjoyed the tour very much,'' Cain said in a
thank-you note to Dean.
   Although she wrote flowery letters to some of the most powerful
people in Washington, Ms. Dean took a jab at many of them in a note
to an aide who had sent her a copy of a Washington's magazine's
1985 list of the capital's ``Social 400,'' which did not bear her
name.
   ``With the exception of Ron &amp; Nancy (Reagan) and Bob &amp; Liddy
(Dole), I wouldn't be seen with any of them!'' she wrote.
   Among others on the list: George and Barbara Bush, Cabinet
secretaries James Baker, George Shultz and Edwin Meese, several
Supreme Court justices and dozens of senators and representatives,
not to mention the richest of the rich.
   Her notes also show signs of the sense of humor friends and
colleagues often recall.
   ``Ba Humbug! I'm not giving back anything!'' she scribbled on a
memo detailing policy against accepting gifts from government
vendors.
   She also was fiercely protective of Pierce, keeping a close eye
on HUD-related news accounts and once warning a public affairs aide
not to include in an internal newsletter some derogatory questions
employees had submitted for Pierce.
   Among them: ``Why do you stay in a job that you wanted to leave
after the election when the president is attempting to eliminate
your key programs?'' and ``Would you like to live out the rest of
your life in a deregulated nursing home?''
   When she sent a copy of the questions to Pierce, she scribbled
one of her frequent one-word notes:
   ``Incredible!''
</TEXT>
