<DOCNO> AP891008-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 1310EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GermanReunification 960   10-08 0929</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-German Reunification, 960</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugees Raise Question of German Reunification</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dramatic rush of refugees from East to
West Germany is causing officials to take a new look at a prospect
once considered remote _ the reunification of that divided country.
   While experts say the formation of one Germany is still not in
the cards for the near future, it is a possibility that can no
longer be dismissed as very remote.
   Any concrete moves toward reunification are likely to worry
people in countries that have twice in this century faced Germans
on the battlefield.
   Raymond G.H. Seitz, assistant secretary of state for European
and Canadian affairs, reaffirmed U.S. support for eventual
unification in testimony before a House Foreign Affairs
subcommittee last week, but added that it must be approached with
caution because of ``a history in which the unification of Germany
led to instability and war.''
   ``The reunification of Germany raises the prospect of major
changes on the continent, and therefore is something we have to
look at very carefully,'' said Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., chairman
of the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on Europe and the Middle
East.
   ``We have kind of paid lip service to it without really thinking
about the implications of it,'' Hamilton said in an interview. ``I
think a lot of countries have done that.''
   The United States and West European governments have long been
on record in favor of reuniting Germany, which was split into two
countries after the Allied victory in World War II and the onset of
the Cold War between East and West.
   A senior U.S. official, speaking on condition he not be
identified, said in an interview, ``A lot of people in Britain,
France, most West European countries, have strong emotional
reservations'' about reunification. ``They haven't had to deal with
those reservations until very recently.''
   Like others interviewed, this official said, ``My own
expectation is that reunification is still a good many years
away.'' But he added, ``If we had been talking a couple of months
ago, I would have said it was very, very remote. The fact that
things are moving in Eastern Europe has obviously changed the
picture.''
   Hamilton said, ``I don't think reunification of Germany is going
to come about in 1990, but it is clearly going to be put on the
agenda now and discussed much more.''
   So far this year, more than 120,000 East Germans have reached
West Germany, where they are granted automatic citizenship. The
exodus has been helped by the decision of the reformist regime in
Hungary to open its borders.
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher has spoken
recently of the possibility of a German confederation, a step short
of complete unity.
   Ingrid Stahmer, deputy mayor of West Berlin, asked about
reunification on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America'' Thursday, said,
``We don't see reunification in that we would form one state again,
but I think that we must come closer....I think that we will come
together on the way to (a United) Europe.''
   But East German historian Siegfried Prokop, asked on the same
program whether unification was in prospect, replied, ``Absolutely
not. It's a dream of the ... reactionary forces in West Germany.''
   Faced with reform movements in Hungary and Poland, the Soviets
are anxious to keep East Germany in their orbit. The country has a
standard of living that is the envy of many of its East Bloc
neighbors, although it remains far below West Germany's.
   Experts said one of the major obstacles to unification is the
absence in East Germany of a strong opposition such as the
Solidarity union which has formed the new government in Poland or
the movements that are bringing about broad political reforms in
Hungary.
   ``I think we are far from a place where this East German regime
or its likely successors are going to move in that direction,''
said Helmut Sonnenfeldt, Berlin-born guest scholar in foreign
policy studies at the liberal-leaning Brookings Institution and
former State Department counselor.
   ``East Germany, in this situation, I don't think has very many
good choices,'' said Hamilton.
   ``There seems to be no way out,'' said Kim Holmes, director of
foreign policy and defense studies for the conservative Heritage
Foundation.
   Still, said Holmes, ``We see the possibility for the first time
of revisiting the German question in a real kind of way. I would
have said a year ago, `Not in my lifetime.' I am beginning to
think, given how swift the events were in Poland and what has
happened with the refugees, that it could happen a lot sooner than
a lot of people think.''
   Sonnenfeldt said the recent developments ``certainly have put
that subject on people's agenda again.''
   ``If one means re-establishing the previous German Reich, even
in a somewhat smaller territory, I think that is probably not in
the cards for any time soon,'' the former State Department official
said.
   ``I think there is a lot of concern in Europe about the
reconstitution of something that resembles the previous United
Germany that existed from 1871 on and especially in the Hitlerian
period,'' he said. ``I think in the United States this is less of a
factor, but I am sure there are particular groups in this country
who would have strong feelings about it.''
   Said Holmes, ``It raises maybe concern, but concern only in the
sense that we are not sure where it might end up. And it could end
up in a number of different ways, some of which could not be in our
interest.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
