<FIRST>r a AM-WrongCharleston     10-08 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wrong Charleston,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ad Offers Help to Hurricane Victims in Wrong Charleston</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper advertisement offering
interest-free home improvement loans for Hurricane Hugo victims
targeted residents of the wrong Charleston.
   The Sears ad ran last week in the Charleston Daily Mail and The
Charleston Gazette. The storm caused some flooding and power
outages in southern West Virginia, but the real damage was in
Charleston, S.C.
   ``Due to the recent damage caused by Hurricane Hugo, we will now
offer 0 percent financing,'' the ad began. It went on to tell
customers they didn't need to wait for insurance checks to begin
repairing their homes and that the loans didn't need to be repaid
for three months.
   The ad listed a telephone number for Sears Credit Central in
Charlotte, N.C.
   ``I think it's pretty obvious in this case it's the wrong
Charleston,'' said Emerson Thomas, an advertising salesman for the
West Virginia-based Charleston newspapers.
   He said the paper was partly to blame for not spotting the error
on the page, ``but then again, they send a camera-ready
(ready-to-print) ad, an insertion order, and we just schedule it,''
he said.
   Susan Bird of the Sears store in Charleston's Town Center Mall
said the ad was probably placed by someone in the Charlotte
district, while the West Virginia stores are part of the Pittsburgh
district.
   ``We don't know at this point how it got in the paper here,''
she said Saturday.
   Sears officials said they did not know whether local stores
would honor the ad. Charleston store manager Peter Martin said he
could not comment without speaking to someone in the main office in
Chicago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
