<FIRST>r w AM-IndianEducation     10-08 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Education,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cavazos Calls for Study Of Indians' Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-College Curriculum Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos criticized
the government's schooling of Native Americans on Sunday and called
for a study that he said ``could prove revolutionary for Indian
education.''
   Cavazos used the 21st National Indian Education Association
Conference in Anchorage, Alaska, to call for a ``federally directed
gathering campaign'' and a special task force ``involving the
participation of Native American citizens and educators'' to
analyze the problems that Native Americans face with education.
   A copy of his speech was released in Washington.
   Cavazos said the results of the survey he called for could have
the same impact as the a 1983 government general education report
that ``shocked the American public and led to the education reform
movement that has come to many areas of the country.''
   ``I see this developing into an `Indian Nations At Risk' study,
which will follow the path laid out by the landmark study of the
national education structure, `A Nation At Risk,''' said Cavazos.
   The education secretary said Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan has
agreed ``that we must move in this direction and the two
departments, Education and Interior, must work together to address
the needs in Indian education.''
   Cavazos and Lujan are the Bush administration's only Hispanic
Cabinet members. The education secretary, a Texan like President
Bush, was first appointed by former President Reagan as the first
Hispanic to the Cabinet.
   Briefly recounting the history of Native Americans, Cavazos
said, ``Long before the appearance of the Anglo on the shores of
the North American continent, you nations had instituted systems of
education.
   ``The first treaty signed with the newly independent United
States in 1794 by the Oneida, Tuscarora and Stockbridge tribes
provided for Indian education,'' he said.
   ``The respect for knowledge held by Native Americans makes the
failures of effective education policies for the Indian nations
these past two centuries all the more tragic,'' said Cavazos,
noting an article that described ``the history of Indian education
(as one) of crossed purposes and unfulfilled hopes that is still
unfolding today.''
   An Education Department study of high school sophomores found
that from 1980 through 1986, American Indians and Alaskan Natives
dropped out at more than double the rate for the whole test group.
   Native American students are likely to be labeled handicapped or
learning disabled, the study said. Eleven percent of Indian
sophomores in public and private schools were enrolled in special
education programs and 36 percent were classified as having some
form of handicap.
   In comparison, 9 percent blacks and 7 percent of Hispanics were
in special programs.
   Cavazos said the 1980 census found only about 8 percent of
American Indians 25 years and older had completed four years of
college. He said a recent study revealed that nearly three out of
four American Indian college students do not earn degrees.
   The statistics are due partly to the government's failed
attempts to at first assimilate Native Americans and then to
urbanize them, he said.
   Now, Cavazos said, the federal government is trying to replace
assimilation with self-determination. He said these efforts are
being bolstered by the administration's education initiatives like
choice _ allowing parents to decide where to send their children to
school _ and school-based management, where principals, teachers,
parents and students set their own curricula, agendas and plans.
   He said the study he wants must provide a complete review of
government programs that affect Indian education. The focus will be
on the cost effectiveness of current efforts, as well as developing
cooperation between the Bureau of Indian Affairs and the Education
Department.
</TEXT>
