<SECOND>AM-Davis Funeral,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private Funeral and Memorial Service Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of screen legend Bette Davis, who died
in France at the age of 81, will be flown to Los Angeles this week
for a private funeral, her attorney said Sunday.
   The two-time Oscar winner, who had battled breast cancer for
several years, died Friday night at the American Hospital in Paris.
   She had been en route to her West Hollywood, Calif., home from
the San Sebastian Film Festival in Spain, where she had been
honored for her 60-year acting career that included 10 Oscar
nominations.
   Her lawyer, Harold Schiff, said final arrangements to return
Miss Davis' body to the United States could not be made until
government offices in France opened Monday.
   Miss Davis _ who appeared in more than 80 films, including
``Jezebel,'' ``All About Eve,'' and ``Of Human Bondage'' _ had
battled breast cancer since a 1983 mastectomy, Schiff said. Within
months of that surgery, she also suffered a stroke and broken hip.
   Schiff said he and Miss Davis' son, Michael Merrill, planned to
arrange a ``very private funeral and a memorial service in a week
or two.'' Both would be held on the West Coast.
   Miss Davis also is survived by two daughters, Barbara Hyman and
Margot Merrill.
