<FIRST>r a AM-CentralParkJogger     10-08 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central Park Jogger,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jogger's Injury Inspires Central Park Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly six months after the brutal rape of a
Central Park jogger, the 29-year-old woman is recovering and
sending messages to a group of fellow runners who are helping make
the park safer for everyone who uses its green expanse.
   Police have beefed up park security and volunteers are
patrolling the park, offering partners for runners and bringing
groups of them together for safer exercise.
   ``This is how good comes from bad,'' said Debbie King, director
of the New York Road Runners Safety Program.
   The jogger, an investment banker, was attacked by a mob of
teen-agers as she ran alone in the northern part of the park, late
in the evening of April 19.
   When police found the woman hours later, she was in a coma and
had lost three-quarters of her blood. Paramedics did not expect her
to live.
   She remained in critical condition until May 1, when she
appeared to raise her eyebrows as her name was called and raised
her hand.
   She was walking a bit when she was moved June 7 to Gaylord
Hospital in Wallingford, Conn.
   By midsummer, she reportedly was classified as a 7 on a recovery
scale of 1 to 8. Patients must reach level 8 to live independently.
She was able to read novels, relearn basic math skills and call
colleagues at Solomon Brothers, where she had worked before the
attack.
   Gaylord spokeswoman Lori Ann Brass said last week that the
jogger was ``making good progress, doing well.'' She would not
elaborate.
   Fred Lebow, president of the New York Road Runners, said he had
never met the injured jogger but received communications from her
through a mutual friend.
   ``I get little messages from her that she jogs a little bit at
Gaylord and that she hopes someday to run the marathon,'' said
Lebow.
   ``She's inspirational to anyone _ not just runners,'' said
Lebow. ``She came through a horrendous experience and evidently
she's recovering.''
   Six youths have been indicted in the attack; hearings are
scheduled for Tuesday although no trial date has been set.
   The case focused the energy of the city's legions of joggers who
were unwilling to surrender the huge park, which stretches 2{ miles
long and a half-mile wide through the center of Manhattan.
   In June, the Road Runners launched its safety program, in which
200 men and women take turns walking or running along a course in
the park in shifts from 7 a.m. to 9 p.m. The joggers carry
lightweight radios and wear bright orange vests.
   ``They are the eyes and ears of the Central Park community,''
Ms. King said. ``The police can't be everywhere; citizens have to
take responsibility.''
   The volunteers have used the radios to report bicycle accidents,
stone-throwing incidents, a car accident and a sexual assault; last
month, a man who allegedly fondled two female joggers was arrested
15 minutes after they flagged down a Road Runner volunteer for help.
   ``There is a very positive feeling among people in Central Park
toward the people in the orange vests. ... It really boosts the
community morale in Central Park,'' Ms. King said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
