<FIRST>r a AM-OperaStrike     10-08 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Opera Strike,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contract Rejected, NY City Opera Cancels Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York City Opera canceled the remaining
six weeks of its never-opened fall season Sunday after striking
orchestra members overwhelmingly rejected a contract offer, the
company's lawyer said.
   Members of Local 802 of the Associated Musicians of Greater New
York voted 56-4 against the four-year proposal, the union announced
Sunday. They have been on strike since Sept. 13 _ what would have
been the season's opening night.
   In addition to the orchestra members, 300 to 400 performers and
backstage personnel are idled by the strike, said Martin
Oppenheimer, the opera's attorney and lead negotiator.
   ``The human loss is obviously significant and very
regrettable,'' Oppenheimer said. Equally important, he added, is
``the cultural loss to this community.''
   The contract voted down Saturday would have guaranteed the
musicians 29 weeks of work per year, the same number of weeks as
the previous contract, and raised wages and benefits 6{ percent
each year, Oppenheimer said. The opera initially sought to cut the
minimum work year to 23 weeks.
   Union spokeswoman Judy West said members believed the deal
didn't go far enough in improving wages and benefits.
   Under the old contract, orchestra members made $755 per 19\-hour
week.
   No new talks were scheduled but both sides said they probably
would meet soon, in hopes of saving the opera's spring season.
   The opera company was established in 1943.
</TEXT>
