<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 1448EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HalfMoon     10-08 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Half Moon,0339</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Replica of Henry Hudson's Ship To Sail on Shakedown Cruise</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly four centuries after explorer Henry
Hudson sailed up the river that bears his name, a replica of his
ship, the Half Moon, will journey down the Hudson River on its
maiden journey.
   The new Half Moon, with a crew of 20, will set out downriver on
its shakedown cruise this coming Saturday, making an overnight stop
in New York City, Andrew Hendricks, who conceived the project,
announced Saturday.
   The crew will then sail it down the Atlantic Coast on a two-week
cruise to the ship's new home at Washington, N.C., on the western
side of Pamlico Sound, Hendricks said. Plans for future voyages are
undecided, he said.
   The Half Moon was built to honor the Netherlands' contributions
to America and Hudson's 1609 voyage up the river, when the English
explorer was working for the Dutch East India Co.
   The 85-foot, 120-ton replica is a little different from Hudson's
``Halve Maen.'' This Half Moon features such non-authentic features
as an emergency engine and contemporary navigational equipment.
   ``You play a fine line with the historical thing,'' said
Hendricks, citing constraints such as Coast Guard regulations,
``but it's as historically accurate as it can be.''
   The ship originally was set to embark on a tour of several
Northeastern ports on July 5. But the June death of the ship's
architect and chief builder, Nicholas Benton, who fell from the
mast of another ship, forced a change of plans.
   ``We had blueprints ... but it didn't say what some of the sizes
of the parts were, or the colors,'' Hendricks said.
   Hendricks also had to hire people to do work that Benton would
have done for free, boosting the cost from $1 million to about $1.2
million, he said.
   Hendricks said he hopes to pay for the Half Moon by charging
admission at a planned visitor center in Washington, N.C.
</TEXT>
