<HEAD>USAir Mechanic Killed When Lightning Strikes Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bolt of lightning struck a jetliner
taxiing on the ground at Orlando International Airport, killing a
ground-crew member who was helping guide it, officials said. No one
aboard the plane was hurt.
   Phil Cataney, a 25-year employee, died en route to the hospital
after being struck Saturday evening, police said.
   He was standing near the nose of the DC-9, helping guide it out
of a gate, when he was hit, said USAir spokeswoman Patricia
Goldman. Witnesses reported seeing the bolt arc from the plane.
   None of the 110 charter passengers aboard the plane, bound for
Philadelphia, was injured, Ms. Goldman said.
   Skies were partly cloudy, but there was no thunderstorm activity
reported in the area at the time. There was no apparent physical
damage to the plane but it was taken out of service for an
inspection, Ms. Goldman said.
   The passengers were delayed in Ornaldo for about 2{ hours while
another plane was brought in.
