<DOCNO> AP891008-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 1602EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     10-08 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Leader Says Talks Deadlocked Over Syrian Withdrawal, Christian
Reform</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TAI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDULLAH AL-SHEHRI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIF, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Lebanese Moslem legislator
said Sunday that talks on ending his country's civil war were
deadlocked and that a ``more vicious war'' could break out unless
Christians surrender some political power.
   Zaher Khatib, a Sunni Moslem who represents the National Front,
an alliance of 18 Syrian and Iranian-backed Lebanese factions, told
reporters that Syria will not withdraw its troops from Lebanon
until the Christians agree to political reforms.
   ``We're at a dangerous crossroads,'' he said after 63 Lebanese
lawmakers failed to meet for the third straight day because of deep
divisions on the central issue of Syria's military presence in
Lebanon and reforms proposed by the Arab League.
   The 33 Christian and 30 Moslem legislators have been in the
Saudi Arabian resort of Taif since Sept. 30 to discuss proposals to
end Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war. The 22-member Arab League is
sponsoring the meeting.
   Khatib said the meeting was a ``historic and golden
opportunity'' that should not be lost.
   ``The alternative is a renewal of the war, and this time it will
be a more vicious war because the weapons are going to be more
vicious,'' he said.
   The Arab League has proposed that Syrian troops withdraw over
two years from Moslem sectors of Beirut to the Bekaa Valley in the
east. A new Lebanese government then would negotiate future Syrian
military deployments.
   Lebanese Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun, a Maronite Catholic,
has demanded a complete Syrian pullout within six months.
   The Syrians, who consider Lebanon vital to their security
against Israel, have made it clear they will not withdraw before
the Christians agree to share power equally with Moslems.
   They have also linked withdrawal of their 40,000 troops in
Lebanon to an Israeli withdrawal from a border strip in southern
Lebanon. The Israelis have refused to budge despite U.N. pressure.
   Youssef Hammoud, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem Parliament member,
said consultations in Taif were deadlocked for the past three days
by what he called a ``tug of war'' between Moslems and Christians.
   The Christians, dominated by the Maronites, have held most key
posts in Lebanon's government, Parliament, judiciary and army since
independence from France in 1943.
   They were considered the majority then. But Moslems now make up
an estimated 55 percent of the Mediterranean country's 4 million
population.
   The Syrians moved in under an Arab League peacekeeping mandate
in 1976, the year after the civil war broke out. Aoun claims they
abrogated that mandate by openly siding with the Moslems.
   The Syrians insist they have never been asked to leave. But the
Christians claim the Syrians ignored two formal requests by former
presidents Elias Sarkis and Amin Gemayel.
   Aoun, although outgunned and outnumbered, launched a ``war of
liberation'' against the Syrians in March. That touched off six
months of fierce artillery battles that killed more than 900 people
before an Arab League-brokered cease-fire took hold Sept. 22.
   Lebanon's political problems are further complicated by the two
rival governments that have ruled since September 1988; one is led
by Aoun and the other by acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a
Syrian-backed Sunni Moslem.
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia has been in contact with Aoun and Hoss
in an effort to break the deadlock.
   Aoun has made no public comment. But Hoss was quoted by Kuwait's
Al-Seyassah daily Sunday as saying that his side considers the
cease-fire as a ``permanent peace'' rather than just a truce.
   Fahd, King Hassan II of Morocco and President Chadli Bendjedid
of Algeria form the Arab League mediation committee that is trying
to end Lebanon's civil war, which has killed more than 150,000
people.
   A statement from the U.S. State Department circulated to
reporters in Taif Sunday backed the lawmakers' meeting and praised
their ``courageous efforts.''
</TEXT>
