<HEAD>Broadway Play's Stage Manager Dead at Age 42</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Andrew Keasley, stage manager of the
Broadway play ``M. Butterfly,'' died of a heart attack a short time
after collapsing backstage during a performance. He was 42.
   Keasley died Saturday night at St. Clare's Hospital, said John
Springer, a public relations spokesman for the play.
   Keasley had undergone open heart surgery within the last years,
Springer said. He died in an ambulance on the way to the hospital
after he collapsed Saturday night, Springer said.
   Besides ``M. Butterfly,'' Keasley served as stage manager on
Broadway for such productions as ``Equus,'' ``Seesaw,'' ``Hair''
and ``42nd Street.''
   Keasley is survived by his wife, Janet Friedman, his mother and
two brothers.
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete Sunday, but Springer said
services will be held in Keasley's native Rhode Island, with a
memorial service in New York.
