<FIRST>r i AM-ItalyFashions     10-08 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy Fashions,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armani Brings Back the Hippies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spring 1990 will mark the rebirth of flower
power, at least in the fashion world.
   Giorgio Armani, who opened the Italian spring-summer
ready-to-wear shows Sunday with his Emporio line, called on the
young to recall the hippie dress code of their parents _ gypsy
skirts and shawls, vests, tattered jeans, oversized shirts and
jackets, clumpy sandals.
   For beach boys and girls, Armani drew inspiration from the South
Pacific with fishnet and burlap his-and-her sarongs and diaper
shorts.
   Italian beaches have long bade farewell to the bikini of the
1960s, giving way to whole suits for women and surf shorts for men.
   Armani takes the look a step further by delving into grandma's
trunk for those Great Gatsby striped tank suits.
   A gasp went up among Americans attending the early morning show
in the theater of Armani's downtown palazzo at the parade of
bare-breasted woman surrounded by bare-chested men, all wearing
Armani's jeans. Europeans, accustomed to topless bathing, didn't
bat an eyelash.
   The blazer king likes his jackets long and light, with a curved
front like a tulip petal, reminiscent of designs several seasons
ago by Italy's Romeo Gigli.
   There was a touch of Gigli too in the faded pastel shades of the
collection and the rounded uneven hemlines of skirts and dresses.
For summer Armani hikes his hemlines way above his demure winter
length.
   Lightweight pantsuits with ample jackets and baggy trousers and
a series of cool cotton jumpsuits are sure to attract summer city
dwellers.
   Another fashion favorite of the younger set, Franco Moschino,
also showed Sunday morning.
   What attracts the young in Moschino is his irony toward fashion
and the fashion world at large. During his shows he likes to hide
his own beautiful clothes under exaggerations of other designers'
embellishments.
   Thus he once based an entire show on headgear from stovepipes to
teddy bears, mocking Christian Lacroix. At every show he makes a
point of ladening his evening wear with heavy gold chains, a Chanel
trademark.
   Moschino also likes to poke fun at people who live by labels,
often sewing his own label on the outside of an outfit. Last season
he designed a jacket with the words ``very expensive jacket''
stitched on the back in gold letters.
   For spring-summer 1990, Moschino also flirt with the new hippie
trend in a series of multicolored gypsy skirts, jeans outfits and
Mexican-style long vests, but the bulk of his collection was based
on an evening look of basic black and gold.
   His most astonishing outfit was a three-piece suit _ jacket,
brassiere and short skirt _ in glimmery gold fabric, with lavish
gold jewelry and a gold chain belt.
   His most ironic style was a floor-length black chiffon gown with
the letters VIP in gold down the front, with the V incorporated in
the neckline.
   Over the next five days, forty of Italy's top ready-to-wear
designers, including Armani, Versace, Krizia, Biagiotti, Missoni,
Fendi and Ferre will present their styles for next year's warmer
weather.
   Along with beautiful clothes the fashion crowd will be treated
to a night at the famed La Scala Opera house for a performance by
Moscow's Bolshoi theater.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891008-0049 </DOCNO>
