<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-08 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Morning Over North-Central Part Of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures dropped into the 20s early Sunday over the
north-central part of the nation, breaking records at several
cities, while rain was scattered from the Southwest into the
Southeast.
   In contrast to the morning chill far to the north, Miami tied
its record of 92 degrees during the afternoon.
   Temperatures hit the 20s over the northern half of the Plains,
the upper Mississippi Valley and the upper Great Lakes.
   Record lows included 24 at Duluth, Minn.; 22 at International
Falls, Minn.; 22 at Marquette, Mich.; and 27 at Minneapolis-St.
Paul, Minn. Grand Rapids, Mich., tied its record of 28, which has
stood since 1896.
   Sunday's low for the Lower 48 states was 12 at Gunnison, Colo.
   The cold air was forecast to extend over the Ohio Valley by
Monday morning, and frost warnings were posted over north-central
and eastern Ohio, Indiana and Kentucky.
   Afternoon showers and thunderstorms extended over the southern
Florida Peninsula, from northern Florida into southern Georgia,
over the central Gulf of Mexico coast, and from southwestern New
Mexico into southwestern Texas.
   But during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, there were no reports
of even a half-inch of rain.
   Elsewhere, rain was scattered over western Pennsylvania and
northeastern North Carolina.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m EDT ranged from 36
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 97 at Palm Springs and Thermal,
Calif.
