<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     10-08 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Menem Draws Praise And Criticism For Military Amnesty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Menem assessed
the political damage Sunday of his pardons for military officers
accused of human rights violations and found both support and angry
criticism.
   ``President Menem had the courage to untie one of the most
dramatic Gordian knots of Argentine life,'' Clarin, the country's
largest newspaper, commented in an editorial.
   ``This is not to say the presidential measure will be a balm
that miraculously cures all wounds,'' it said, but ``he worked
inspired by the common good.''
   Other expressions of support came from members of the
conservative Union of the Democratic Center, Argentina's third
biggest political party; a Roman Catholic bishop, military figures
and Menem's own Peronist Party.
   But human rights groups and leftist politicians and newspapers
denounced Menem for pardoning 39 officers accused of kidnapping,
torture and murder in the ``dirty war'' against suspected
subversives during the 1976-83 military dictatorships.
   Thousands of Communist Party pamphlets were distributed saying,
``The killers and coup makers of today will be the repressors of
tomorrow.''
   At least 8,960 suspected leftists were arrested, never seen
again and presumed executed, according to a commission appointed by
former President Raul Alfonsin whose election in 1983 ended
military rule. Human rights groups put the total number of victims
who disappeared at 30,000 or more.
   Congressman Federico Storani of Alfonsin's Radical Civic Union,
second in size behind the Peronists, accused Menem of appeasing the
armed forces ``in case their intervention is necessary'' to quell
protests against his economic policies.
   Menem, a 59-year-old former provincial governor, was held under
arrest for nearly five years following the March 1976 military coup
that ousted President Isabel Peron. He was elected president last
May and took office on July 8 amid triple-digit inflation and
rising unemployment.
   Opponents of the pardons said Menem's action was too much in
favor of the military.
   ``It is legitimite to desire that society be reconciled with
itself. But this is not the way,'' Eduardo Luis Duhalde, director
of the leftist newspaper ``Nuevo Sur,'' wrote in a column.
   ``Carlos Saul Menem has committed a grave error ... that in the
end may devour him,'' Duhalde wrote. Reconciliation ``can never be
based on forgetfulness ... putting on the same level victims and
aggressors, killers and killed, martyrs and hangmen.''
   Also pardoned were 174 officers accused of participating in
three rebellions against Alfonsin and three officers _ including
ex-army commander and president Leopoldo Galtieri _ who were jailed
for mishandling the 1982 Falklands War with Britain.
</TEXT>
