<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Carroll Campbell called Sunday for
churches nationwide to join an adopt-a-family program to help South
Carolina victims of Hurricane Hugo.
   ``We'll be back,'' Campbell said. ``With the spirit now in this
state, with the help of America and with the help of God, we'll
rebuild and we'll re-establish and we will endure.''
   Campbell urged churches in other parts of the country to contact
South Carolina affiliates for the names of families in need of
assistance. He asked the churches to provide ``spiritual, material
and moral support'' to adopted families for up to one year.
   Campbell promoted the program, unveiled in Columbia on Thursday,
during a speech to about 300 members of Citadel Square Baptist
Church, a 134-year-old church in downtown Charleston which suffered
some $250,000 in roof, window and other damage. His remarks were
taped for broadcast on the American Christian Television System.
   Hugo hit the Charleston coast Sept. 21 with 135 mph winds,
squashing scores of buildings and leaving thousands without
electricity and other necessities. The storm killed 29 people on
the U.S. mainland and 33 in the Caribbean.
   The storm killed 18 people in South Carolina and did an
estimated $5 billion in damage in 24 counties.
   About 3,000 of South Carolina Electric &amp; Gas' 132,000
Charleston-area customers remained without power Sunday, said
company spokesman Bill Lide.
   ``This long-term recovery process is going to take long-term
support,'' the governor said. ``Many families have lost everything.
They are not going to bounce back from those circumstances. It's
going to take months and maybe years for some of them to get back
on their feet.''
   Campbell said the program was the idea of his wife, Iris.
