<FIRST>r a AM-CocaineSeizure     10-08 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Seizure,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suburban Chiefs of Police Want Credit for Cocaine Raid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chiefs of five small police departments
have protested what they consider undeserved credit given to Los
Angeles police for the seizure of a record 19 tons of cocaine.
   At stake, the chiefs said in a letter to local newspapers and
television stations, is due recognition of their efforts and shares
of the $12.4 million in cash confiscated with the cocaine on Sept.
28.
   Los Angeles Police Chief Daryl F. Gates told the City Council on
Wednesday that his department could expect up to $2 million of the
$12.4 million for its role in the seizure.
   But police chiefs in Arcadia, Bell, Huntington Park, Maywood and
South Gate said Los Angeles played a minor role in the raid on a
warehouse in Sylmar, providing backup security while their
investigators and federal agents searched the warehouse.
   Officers from five smaller departments and two federal Drug
Enforcement Administration agents did surveillance work that led up
to the raid, the chiefs said.
   ``We feel that those cities that were actually responsible
should get the credit, and along with that comes the money,'' Bell
Police Chief Manuel Ortega said Saturday. ``LAPD will get a share
but certainly not the $2 million that Chief Gates spoke of.''
   The chiefs also complained about the amount of attention local
media devoted to Gates' role in the affair.
   Cmdr. William Booth, spokesman for Los Angeles police, said the
media repeatedly ignored Gates' frequent praise for the smaller
departments.
   Federal drug officials have not announced a formula for dividing
up the money seized in the Sylmar drug bust, but said the money was
deposited in an unidentified downtown Los Angeles bank.
   In most cases, a hearing is held before the assets are
distributed to law enforcement agencies. A federal magistrate
determines how much, if any, of the assets represent ill-gotten
gains and should remain confiscated.
   Booth said the city would abide by whatever formula is used by
the federal government.
</TEXT>
