<HEAD>Mason Criticizes Giuliani Campaign Staff</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Jackie Mason says the staff of
Republican mayoral candidate Rudolph Giuliani is so ``incompetent''
that it's hard to know if ``they're running a campaign or they're
running for their life.''
   Mason resigned under pressure from the Giuliani campaign Sept.
27 after remarks that the rabbi-turned-comedian made about blacks
and Jews were published in the Village Voice.
   ``I never saw a more incompetent group of people in my life,''
Mason says of the Giuliani campaign staff in the Oct. 16 issue of
New York magazine.
   ``They look like they don't know if they're running a campaign
or they're running for their life or they should be running for a
bar on Second Avenue.''
   The Voice quoted Mason as saying Democratic mayoral candidate
David Dinkins ``looked like a black model without a job'' and that
Jews vote for blacks because they ``are sick with complexes.''
   In the New York magazine interview, Mason complained about what
he called a double standard that finds Giuliani guilty of racism
when the candidate links Dinkins with Jesse Jackson.
   ``Yet when Dinkins connects Giuliani to Ronald Reagan, he's
considered a political fighter,'' he said.
   But Mason said that ``twenty years ago, the white people were
racists and the blacks were the victims. Today, it's exactly the
opposite.''
   Mason, star of the ABC series ``Chicken Soup,'' also lashed out
at Mayor Edward I. Koch and Jewish leaders.
   Koch's criticism of Mason's remarks are ``like a Nazi calling a
Jew a bigot,'' he said.
   ``Jews are professional victims who practically beg their
persecutors to keep persecuting them,'' he said. Jewish leaders
``do this out of their own sick fears, their own persecution
complexes.''
