<SECOND>BC-Britain-Chess,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Timman Draws Fifth Semifinal Game with Speelman, Keeps Lead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan Timman of the Netherlands played a 43-move
draw with Jon Speelman of England in the fifth game of their World
Chess Championship semifinal Sunday to maintain a one-point lead.
   Timman leads 2.5-1.5 with an unfinished game from the fourth
round scheduled to resume Monday. A win scores one point and a draw
a half.
   Speelman recovered from an inferior opening position to gain
what many experts regarded as good prospects to win. But Timman
maneuvered and it was Speelman who had to defend carefully to hold
a draw.
   In the other semifinal Artur Yusupov took a timeout to postpone
his fifth game with fellow Soviet and former world champion Anatoly
Karpov until Tuesday. Yusupov trails Karpov 1.5-2.5.
   The winner of the Candidates' cycle will challenge world
champion Garri Kasparov in a 24-game match starting in October
1990. The winning semifinalists will face off in the Candidates'
finals in March.
   Yusupov will use the two free days to prepare his fifth game
where he will open with the advantage of the white pieces.
   In their sixth game scheduled for Tuesday, Speelman will play
white against Timman.
</TEXT>
