<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Bus 1stLd-Writethru a0745 10-08 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Bus, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0745,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Die In Bus Fire Blamed on Incendiary Bomb</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout with fire blamed on incendiary bomb; ADDS background
on drug war, byline; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire apparently ignited by an
incendiary bomb broke out on a bus in Bogota Sunday, authorities
reported. They said seven people were killed and at least seven
were injured.
   No individual or group claimed responsibility.
   Police said they had no way of knowing if the incident was
related to a wave of bombings by drug traffickers.
   The bus driver, Luis Fernando Pataquiva, told the radio chain
RCN that a man and a woman apparently left a bomb in the back of
the bus and it exploded moments after they got off.
   Police said seven people were killed and seven injured, but
local news reports said seven were killed and eight injured.
   ``Apparently the fire was caused by an incendiary bomb,'' a
national police spokeswoman said on condition of anonymity. She did
not elaborate.
   Police earlier said the noon fire appeared to have been caused
by a short circuit in the vehicle's electrical system..
   Radio station Caracol reported that a policeman at the scene
said the fire apparently started in a five-gallon plastic container
of gasoline in the back of the bus.
   No one has claimed responsibility for scores of bombings in
Colombian cities since the drug traffickers and government declared
war on each other in mid-August after the assassination of a
presidential candidate. The killing was blamed on drug traffickers.
   Before Sunday's bus explosion there had been 148 bombings that
killed at least 10 people and wounded 164.
</TEXT>
