<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Carlsen 2ndLd-Writethru a0763 10-08 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Carlsen, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0763,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hero Sea Captain Dead at 75</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS to CORRECT middle name to Kurt, sted Jurt; year of initial
storm to 1951, sted 1952; year of sinking to 1952, sted 1953. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOODBRIDGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capt. Henrick Kurt Carlsen, a sea
captain who gained international attention in 1952 for staying
stubbornly aboard his crippled freighter for seven days as it
slowly sank, has died at age 75.
   Carlsen died Saturday at his home in Woodbridge.
   On Dec. 29, 1951, Carlsen was the 37-year-old captain of the
freighter Flying Enterprise when a storm ripped open the ship's
hull in the English Channel.
   After ordering the 40 crewmen and 10 passengers overboard, he
remained with the ship, owned by American Export-Isbrandtsen Lines
of New York, so the vessel could not be claimed for salvage by
another company.
   On Jan. 5, 1952, as another storm began to threaten the ship,
Carlsen and a companion jumped overboard and watched from the
tugboat's deck as the ship sank into the Channel near Falmouth.
   Born in Denmark, Carlsen came to United States in 1938. He
worked for the New York-based shipping line from 1944 until his
retirement in 1976.
</TEXT>
