<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 2318EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     10-08 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Incidents During Voter Registration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second of four voter-registration
days for February's elections proceeded without incident Sunday,
Electoral Council officials said.
   Opposition representatives in one city said, however, that they
would file a complaint about irregularities.
   Officials earlier had said they hoped to register 500,000 voters
Sunday, but they had no figures available late in the day because
information was incomplete from the 4,934 registration precincts.
They said figures should be available by the middle of the week.
   In Leon, 55 miles west of Managua, a representative of the
opposition National Opposition Union said by telephone the group
will present complaints about alleged registration irregularities
committed by electoral officials. There were no immediate details.
   Before elections take place Feb. 25, officials hope to register
1.92 million Nicaraguans age 16 and older. Voter registration is
taking place during the four Sundays in October.
   The government said more than 370,000 people registered to vote
last Sunday on the first day of registration. It said registration
was hampered in some rural areas last Sunday because of rebel
activity, but no such incidents were reported this time.
   Soldiers were stationed at voter registration locations in rural
provinces where anti-government guerrillas have been active, the
government said.
   The Defense Ministry reported three rebels and one government
soldier were killed Saturday when insurgents attacked a military
patrol in El Nisperal, 130 miles southeast of Managua.
   Rebel attacks have been sporadic this year since a cease-fire
was signed between the government and rebels known as Contras. Five
Central American presidents agreed in August to resettle the
Contras, most of whom are based across the border in Honduras. In
return, the Nicaraguan government has promised free elections and
political reforms.
   The Contras have been fighting the ruling Sandinistas since
1981. They claim the Sandinistas' shift to the far left betrayed
the revolution that ousted conservative President Anastasio Somoza
in 1979, ending 42 years of family rule.
</TEXT>
