<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 2327EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nigeria     10-08 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nigeria,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aspiring Politicians Criticize Military's Shutdown Of Parties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Gen. Ibrahim Babangida's
military government caught the nation and aspiring politicians by
surprise Sunday with its decision to dissolve prospective parties
and create two from scratch.
   Babangida, in a nationwide radio address Saturday night, said
none of the 13 parties that applied to be one of two legal parties
``had passed the test as imposed by our vision of a new political
order.''
   The candidate parties had ties to earlier parties that showed
signs of being ethnic groupings the military would not tolerate,
Babangida said.
   Babangida said limiting the country to two parties, funded only
by the government, was the only way to avoid the parties becoming
hostage to regional, ethnic or religious groups in this West
African country of 100 million.
   David Iornem, spokesman for the People's Solidarity Party, said
Babangida's move was an attack on the political class.
   Dr. Said Ngamdu of the Nigerian National Congress Party said,
``My heart bleeds when I think of the colossal amount of money,
time, physical and mental energy expended by the National Electoral
Commission and the political associations (parties).''
   Nigeria, an oil-producing nation that has seen its economy near
collapse from mismanagement, corruption and falling oil prices, has
been ruled by military men for 20 of its 29 years since
independence from Britain.
   The government's strict austerity program, adopted at the
insistence of international creditors, sharply reduced the standard
of living. Demonstrations against the measures erupted into riots
that left at least 43 people dead in May.
</TEXT>
