<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 1504EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Gulf-EEC     10-08 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gulf-EEC,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Oil Nations To Hold Talks With EEC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Organization of Arab
Oil Exporting Countries said Sunday it will hold talks in December
with the European Economic Community.
   The OAPEC group will be led by Mana Saeed Oteiba, oil minister
of the United Arab Emirates, in talks intended to enable the two
sides to exchange views on energy-related matters.
   The meeting at the European Community's headquarters in Brussels
will be the second of its kind in a decade, said Abdul-Aziz
al-Wattari, OAPEC assistant secretary-general.
   The organization is composed of the U.A.E., Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain, Iraq, Syria, Egypt, Algeria, Libya and
Tunisia.
   Among the OAPEC states are five members of the six-nation Gulf
Cooperation Council, which has been trying to persuade the EEC to
lift duties on petrochemical exports under a trade cooperation pact.
   The council also is in contact with the EEC to assess the impact
of the single European market coming into force in 1992 on their
relations, particularly on Gulf overseas investments.
   Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain and the U.A.E., along with
Oman, which is not a member of OAPEC, account for roughly 20
percent of the non-Communist world's 52 million barrels per day of
oil output, and hold 45 percent of global oil reserves.
   Seven OAPEC states also are members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, which also recently initiated
contacts with the EEC on cooperation in stabilizing world oil
prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
