<DOCNO> AP891008-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 1822EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-OilSeminar     10-08 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Seminar,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Oil Producers Advised To Escalate Oil Exploration</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf-EEC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab petroleum-producing
countries were urged by experts Sunday to increase exploration in
order to boost reserves and prevent shortages in the next century.
   Current Arab oil reserves plus recoverable reserves and
anticipated discoveries can satisfy oil demand until 2020, said
Abdul-Aziz al-Wattari, assistant secretary-general of the
Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   ``But a gap between supply and demand will then occur unless new
reserves are discovered to help meet the accelerating demand for
energy from hydrocarbons,'' Wattari said in an inaugural speech of
a four-day seminar in Abu Dhabi.
   The four-day seminar on ``Deep Formations in the Arab Countries:
Hydrocarbon Potential and Exploration Techniques,'' is the first of
its kind in the Gulf and was organized by OAPEC and the Abu Dhabi
National Oil Co.
   Wattari told over 70 participants that world energy consumption
has been increasing in recent years and was expected to continue
rising in the coming years.
   ``Increases in oil production and reserves should match that.
And some oil experts forecast that oil production will peak at 75
million barrels per day in the year 2010,'' he said.
   Daily world oil output currently is 62 million barrels, of which
the Arab world accounts for roughly 18 million barrels.
   He urged Arab states to make use of new advanced exploration
techniques developed in Western countries.
   ADNOC General Manager Sohail al-Mazroui, backing Wattari's call,
said expanded oil exploration was ``essential in order to guarantee
the continuation of petroleum supplies at their current level.
Experts believe there will be an increased global dependence on
Arab oil as reserves of other oil-producing nations will vanish in
the future.''
   
 
</TEXT>
