<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 1825EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CoalStrike     10-08 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trumka Says Strike Will Continue Until Contract Reached</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOGAN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Mine Workers President Richard Trumka
promised Sunday that the union's bitter strike against Pittston
Coal Group Inc. will continue until a contract is reached.
   ``How long are we willing to go? One day longer than Pittston,''
Trumka told a solidarity rally attended by 1,500 miners and
retirees and their families.
   The UMW has been striking Pittston in Virginia, Kentucky and
West Virginia since April in a contract dispute over health and
insurance benefits.
   Miners from West Virgina, Virginia, Kentucky and Ohio attended
the rally pledging to continue selective strikes against Pittston
and other companies the union says supplies the nation's second
largest coal exporter.
   Last week, a Virginia judge fined the union $6.9 million for
illegal strike activities, bringing the total fines assessed during
the strike to more than $30 million.
   But Trumka said the union has enough money to continue the
strike.
   ``We have ample resources to take care of our strikers
indefinitely,'' said Trumka. He added that striking miners now are
eligible to apply for $1,000 interest-free loans from the union.
   Last week the 80,000-member UMW rejoined the 14 million-member
AFL-CIO after a 40-year separation.
   Trumka said the affiliation merely formalized a working
cooperation the miners' union has had with the AFL-CIO.
</TEXT>
