<DOCNO> AP891008-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-89 1955EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-DrugRecall     10-08 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Recall,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Generic Drug Maker Complies With FDA Call To Recall Medication</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pharmaceutical maker on Sunday voluntarily
began the recall of a generic antibiotic used to treat urinary
tract infections a day after the federal Food and Drug
Administration requested the action.
   The FDA contends that Bolar Pharmaceutical Co. Inc., based in
Copiague, cheated on product safety tests when it submitted the
drug, nitrofurantoin, for FDA approval.
   Robert Shulman, president of the company, said in a statement
that the recall of the 100 mg capsules was in response to questions
raised by the FDA.
   ``Bolar is concerned first with the ongoing well-being of the
people who use our drugs,'' Shulman said. ``The charges that have
been made against this product and our company warrant this
cautious move on our part while we investigate to determine where
the truth lies.''
   An FDA investigation found indications that Bolar substituted
the brand name drug Macrodantin for its generic version in tests
three years ago to win approval of the generic product, FDA
spokesman Jeff Nesbit said.
   ``We believe that this occurrence is not of Bolar's doing,''
Shulman said, adding that the product tested by the FDA was not the
same product it provided for laboratory testing.
   Because of the evidence of a substitution, the FDA contends it
is not possible to determine whether the Bolar product is
equivalent to the brand-name product, which is made by
Norwich-Eaton Pharmaceuticals.
   Bolar, which is the largest of the generic drug makers under FDA
scrutiny, won approval for its generic version of nitrofurantoin in
June 1988.
   Bolar's product is the only generic drug approved as
therapeutically equivalent to Macrodantin, although other dosage
forms of nitrofurantoin are available.
   The FDA also is investigating other generic drugs made by Bolar
as part of its probe of more than a dozen generic drug companies in
the wake of allegations of fraud and corruption within the industry
and FDA's generic drug division.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
